sic and Literacy: A New Approach to Education -- tPART 6. Communicating Empowerment -- t18. “Thanks God for the Twitter and the Facebook! Thanks God for That!” -- t19. The New Storytellers of Afghanistan -- t20. Six Epiphanies: Testament to Change from Inside an Afghan Orphanage -- tEpilogue: Imagining the Future -- tSelected Bibliography and Filmography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive look at youth living in a country attempting to rebuild itself after three decades of civil conflict, Children of Afghanistan relies on the research and fieldwork of twenty-one experts to cover an incredible range of topics. Focusing on the full scope of childhood, from birth through young adulthood, this edited volume examines a myriad of issues: early childhood socialization in war and peace; education, literacy, vocational training, and apprenticeship; refugee life; mental and physical health, including disabilities and nutrition; children’s songs, folktales, and art; sports and play; orphans; life on the streets; child labor and children as family breadwinners; child soldiers and militarization; sexual exploitation; growing up in prison; marriage; family violence; and other issues vital to understanding, empowerment, and transformation. Children of Afghanistan is the first volume that not only attempts to analyze the range of challenges facing Afghan children across class, gender, and region but also offers solutions to the problems they face. With nearly half of the population under the age of fifteen, the future of the country no doubt lies with its children. Those who seek peace for the region must find solutions to the host of crises that have led the United Nations to call Afghanistan “the worst place on earth to be born.” The authors of Children of Afghanistan provide child-centered solutions to rebuilding the country’s cultural, social, and economic institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAnwari, Hangama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAssefa, Fitsum, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrel, Annalies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoutin, Delphine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodsky, Anne E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler-Broyles, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufour, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEggerman, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Jennifer, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHyneman, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKator-Mubarez, Amina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMohib, Lael Adams, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOates, Lauryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmar, Wahid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPanter-Brick, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPascale, Louise M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPounds, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aQargha, Omar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaito, Mamiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSharif, Sharifa, econtributor.4